        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(providers/openrouter): treat OpenRouter (URL + default route) as long-TTL-eligible for Anthropic cache_control",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n`isLongTtlEligibleEndpoint()` decides whether the env-driven `OPENCLAW_CACHE_RETENTION=long` default (and conservative implicit-long behavior) promotes an Anthropic `cache_control` marker from the 5-minute to the 1-hour `ttl`. It only whitelisted `api.anthropic.com` and Google Vertex hosts — even though OpenRouter is the standard path for Anthropic models in many deployments, including the one in #9600, and explicitly supports the same `cache_control: { type: \"ephemeral\", ttl: \"1h\" }` shape ([OpenRouter prompt caching docs](https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/best-practices/prompt-caching#anthropic-claude)).\n\nThis PR makes **both** OpenRouter routes long-TTL eligible under env-driven defaults.\n\n## Update addressing review feedback (default-route coverage)\n\nThe earlier revision only covered concrete `openrouter.ai` baseUrl routes. As [@clawsweeper flagged](https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/91237), `createOpenRouterSystemCacheWrapper()` also treats `provider: \"openrouter\"` with **no `baseUrl`** as a verified default OpenRouter route, but it passed `undefined` into `resolveAnthropicEphemeralCacheControl(...)` — so `OPENCLAW_CACHE_RETENTION=long` still emitted the 5-minute marker on that supported default route.\n\nFixed by reusing the verified-route fact the wrapper already computes:\n\n- `resolveAnthropicEphemeralCacheControl()` gains an optional `longTtlEligibleRoute` argument. When a caller has *already* verified the route is long-TTL-eligible, it opts that route into implicit/env-driven 1-hour TTL even when `baseUrl` is undefined and hostname gating can't see it.\n- `createOpenRouterSystemCacheWrapper()` only reaches the cache-marker patch path after asserting the route is OpenRouter (`endpointClass === \"openrouter\"` or the `default` route with `provider === \"openrouter\"`). It now passes `longTtlEligibleRoute = true` so both the concrete-URL and default routes behave consistently.\n\nDefaults stay conservative: unverified/unknown routes still require an explicit `cacheRetention: \"long\"` opt-in for the 1-hour marker.\n\n| Endpoint | `OPENCLAW_CACHE_RETENTION=long` env | `cacheRetention: \"long\"` explicit |\n|---|---|---|\n| `api.anthropic.com` | ✅ 1h | ✅ 1h |\n| Vertex AI | ✅ 1h | ✅ 1h |\n| **`openrouter.ai` baseUrl** | **❌ 5m → ✅ 1h** | ✅ 1h |\n| **OpenRouter default route (no baseUrl)** | **❌ 5m → ✅ 1h (this revision)** | ✅ 1h |\n| Custom proxy / unknown host | ❌ 5m (unchanged) | ✅ 1h (unchanged) |\n\n## Why this matters\n\nFor workloads dominated by spaced-out cron / one-shot subagent runs, the default 5-min TTL expires between runs and forces a fresh ~89K-token prefix cache write each time. From `openclaw status --verbose` on the deployment behind #9600:\n\n- Interactive sessions (back-to-back turns within 5 min): **88% cache hit ✅**\n- Cron / one-shot subagent sessions (spaced > 5 min apart): **1%, 33%, 33%, 72%, 87% — wildly variable ❌**\n\nThe 1h-TTL cache write costs 2x base input instead of 1.25x, so the breakeven is ~8 reads inside the hour — easily met on any account with regular cron / agent activity. The OpenRouter default route is the path most cron/subagent deployments actually use (canonical `provider: \"openrouter\"`, no explicit baseUrl), which is exactly why the default-route gap mattered.\n\n## Tests\n\n`src/agents/anthropic-payload-policy.long-ttl-eligibility.test.ts` (11 cases) — adds, on top of the prior 7:\n\n- Verified OpenRouter default route (`baseUrl` undefined, `longTtlEligibleRoute=true`) + env long → `ttl: \"1h\"` (**new — the default-route fix**)\n- Verified route with explicit `cacheRetention: \"long\"` + `baseUrl` undefined → `ttl: \"1h\"`\n- **Un**verified default route (`longTtlEligibleRoute=false`) + env long → stays on the 5-minute marker (conservative gating preserved)\n- `cacheRetention: \"none\"` on a verified route → still `undefined` (no marker)\n\n`src/agents/embedded-agent-runner/extra-params.openrouter-cache-control.test.ts` — adds a wrapper-level end-to-end regression test: `provider: \"openrouter\"` with **no baseUrl** under `OPENCLAW_CACHE_RETENTION=long` now stamps `cache_control: { type: \"ephemeral\", ttl: \"1h\" }` on the system block (env saved/restored per test).\n\nTargeted run (58 passing across the touched suites):\n\n```\n✓ src/agents/anthropic-payload-policy.long-ttl-eligibility.test.ts (11 tests)\n✓ src/agents/embedded-agent-runner/extra-params.openrouter-cache-control.test.ts (9 tests)\n✓ src/agents/embedded-agent-runner-extraparams-openrouter.test.ts (9 tests)\n✓ src/llm/providers/stream-wrappers/proxy.test.ts (10 tests)\n✓ src/llm/providers/stream-wrappers/anthropic-cache-control-payload.test.ts (1 test)\n```\n\n`tsc --noEmit` clean; `oxlint` + `oxfmt --check` clean on all four touched files.\n\n## Verification\n\n- Unit + wrapper-level tests above prove the default-route behavior (the exact gap raised in review) without needing a live provider.\n- Did NOT change: explicit `cacheRetention: \"long\"` behavior on any route, or the conservative gating for unknown/custom proxies.\n- Real-provider proof note: the wrapper-level test asserts the transport-facing payload body carries `ttl: \"1h\"` on the default route, which is the same JSON OpenClaw sends to OpenRouter. A maintainer with a live OpenRouter Anthropic route can confirm via `openclaw status --verbose` cache-hit metrics over a cron-spaced workload.\n\n## Refs\n\n- Resolves the OpenRouter-side scope of #9600\n- OpenRouter docs support `\"ttl\": \"1h\"` for Anthropic via `cache_control`: https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/best-practices/prompt-caching#anthropic-claude\n",
        "branch": "fix/openrouter-1h-cache-ttl-eligibility",
